        "orario": "17:06",
        "timestamp": 1773417979,
        "contenuto_esteso": "To display this content from YouTube, you must enable advertisement tracking and audience measurement. One of your browser extensions seems to be blocking the video player from loading. To watch this content, you may need to disable it on this site. As 800,000 flee, half of Lebanon lives in war zones without markets, supplies or healthcare Middle East Issued on: 13/03/2026 - 17:06 Genie Godula is pleased to welcome Hassan Al-Sayed. Field Coordinator for the NGO Solidarités International, joining us from Saida in southern Lebanon, a city that has rapidly transformed into a refuge for hundreds of thousands displaced. A significant proportion of the population remains trapped in areas exposed to daily bombardment, unable to leave due to poverty, disability, age, or family responsibilities. The psychological trauma experienced by displaced families and those trapped in conflict zones underscores the sheer cruelty and profound human cost of war. Lebanon’s Mission Impossible: Could US and Israeli pressure to disarm Hezbollah lead to civil war? 13/03/2026 Middle East Strait of Hormuz: Iran leverages control of a critical chokepoint in the global oil trade 13/03/2026 Middle East 'Mental, subjective impact': Iran taking on 'American might' with cyberterrorism 13/03/2026 Middle East Israel widens Lebanon bombing campaign to target north and central Beirut 13/03/2026 On the ground Middle East Netanyahu says new Iran leader 'can't show his face in public' 12/03/2026 Middle East Iran to allow India-flagged tankers to pass through Strait of Hormuz (reports) 12/03/2026 Middle East US Democrats call for 'swift investigation' into strike on Iranian school 12/03/2026 Middle East Middle East war: Dubai targeted by fresh Iranian drone strikes 12/03/2026 Middle East Iran's new supreme leader's first statement: Takeaways, optics, messaging 12/03/2026 Middle East"
